19 Be It Enacted by the Legislature of the State of Idaho:
20 SECTION 1. That Section 39-1101, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
21 amended to read as follows:
22 39-1101. POLICY. It is hereby declared to be the policy of this state
23 to establish a minimum statewide system for the protection of children in
24 daycare facilities. This system is intended to establish minimum standards,
25 while still leaving primary responsibility for evaluation and selection of
26 daycare services with parents. The minimum standards established by this
27 chapter shall not be construed as preempting more stringent regulation by
28 county or city ordinance.
29 SECTION 2. That Section 39-1102, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
30 amended to read as follows:
31 39-1102. DEFINITIONS. As used in this chapter:
32 (1) "Board" means the Idaho board of health and welfare.
33 (2) "Child" means a person less than thirteen (13) years of age.
34 (3) "Daycare" means care and supervision provided for compensation
35 during part of a twenty-four (24) hour day, for a child or children not
36 related by blood, marriage or legal guardianship to the person or persons
37 providing the care, in a place other than the child's or children's own home
38 or homes.
39 (4) "Daycare center" means a place or facility providing daycare for
40 compensation for thirteen (13) or more children.

2
1 (5) "Daycare facility" means a place or facility providing daycare
2 services for compensation to seven (7) or more children not related to the
3 provider.
4 (6) "Department" means the Idaho department of health and welfare.
5 (7) "Employee" means any person working for compensation in a facility
6 that provides daycare.
7 (8) "Family daycare home" means a home, place, or facility providing
8 daycare for six (6) or fewer children.
9 (9) "Group daycare facility" means a home, place, or facility providing
10 daycare for seven (7) to twelve (12) children.
11 (10) "Group size" means the maximum number of children in one (1) group
12 or classroom.
13 (11) "Mixed age group" means a care group that includes children of mul-
14 tiple ages.
15 (12) "Ratio" means the number of staff required to supervise a certain
16 number of children.
17 (13) "Single age group" means a care group that includes children of
18 similar age.
19 (14) "Supervision" means:
20 (a) For a child less than five (5) years of age, a provider is within
21 sight or normal hearing range of the child and near enough to render im-
22 mediate assistance to the child;
23 (b) For a child five (5) years of age and older, a provider is within
24 sight or normal hearing range of the child as appropriate to the child's
25 individual age, needs, and capabilities; and
26 (c) Notwithstanding paragraph (b) of this subsection, for all children
27 while sleeping, swimming or engaging in other water activity involving
28 a pool, hot tub, or other body of water, or on field trips or activities
29 away from the facility, a provider is within sight and normal hearing
30 range of the child.
31 (14) (15) "Training" means continuing education in child development
32 areas relating to child care. Training can be acquired through a variety of
33 methods including, but not limited to, the viewing of audio visual materi-
34 als, correspondence courses, community workshops and in-house training.
35 SECTION 3. That Section 39-1104, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
36 amended to read as follows:
37 39-1104. APPLICATION FOR LICENSE -- FIRE SAFETY AND HEALTH INSPEC-
38 TIONS. (1) Application. A person who wishes to operate a daycare facility
39 shall be a minimum of eighteen (18) years of age, shall submit an application
40 on the forms provided by the department, and shall obtain the required cer-
41 tificates of inspection as provided herein.
42 (2) Inspections. A person who wishes to operate a daycare facility
43 shall submit: (a) a certificate of a fire inspection of the proposed center,
44 conducted by a fire department or fire district official, establishing com-
45 pliance with the minimum standards specified in section 39-1109, Idaho Code;
46 and (b) a health and safety inspection of the proposed facility conducted by
47 a qualified inspector as designated by the department, establishing compli-
48 ance with the minimum standards specified in sections 39-1109 and 39-1110,
49 Idaho Code.

3
1 (3) Continued compliance and reinspection. Daycare facilities shall
2 at all times maintain compliance with the safety and health requirements
3 identified in this chapter. The department may cause any daycare facility to
4 be reinspected during the term of a license for safety and health compliance
5 as determined necessary by the department. No charge for any reinspection
6 after the initial inspection in any license period shall be made to the day-
7 care facility.
8 (4) If an applicant fails to complete the application process within
9 six (6) months, the application will be considered abandoned and shall be
10 terminated. An applicant whose application is abandoned, and subsequently
11 terminated, may start a new application at any time.
12 SECTION 4. That Section 39-1106, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
13 amended to read as follows:
14 39-1106. ISSUANCE OF LICENSE -- RENEWAL. (1) Upon receipt of the
15 completed application, inspection certificates and the criminal his-
16 tory, the department shall, upon a finding of compliance with the minimum
17 standards set forth in this chapter, issue a basic daycare license to the ap-
18 plicant. The license shall be valid for two (2) years, unless revoked or sus-
19 pended, and shall be posted in a conspicuous place at the daycare facility.
20 (2) The department shall send a renewal application to the owner of the
21 daycare facility no later than ninety (90) days prior to the expiration of
22 an existing license. The owner shall submit to the department the renewal
23 application with the required renewal fee and a criminal history check prior
24 to the expiration of the existing license. A complete criminal history check
25 shall be provided for any new persons requiring a criminal history check in
26 accordance with section 39-1105, Idaho Code.
27 (3) Criminal history checks on those persons under eighteen (18) years
28 of age shall include a check of the juvenile justice records of adjudications
29 of the magistrate division of the district court, county probation services
30 and department records as authorized by the minor and his parent or guardian.
31 (4) The department shall maintain a list of all licensees for public
32 use.
33 (5) Submission of a renewal application, fee and required criminal
34 history check shall entitle the daycare facility owner to continue daycare
35 services, subject to action by the department pursuant to section 39-1113,
36 Idaho Code.
37 SECTION 5. That Section 39-1108, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
38 repealed.
39 SECTION 6. That Section 39-1109, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
40 amended to read as follows:
41 39-1109. SAFETY STANDARDS. (1) Daycare facilities, owners and opera-
42 tors shall comply with the following safety standards in the area of the day-
43 care facility in which daycare is provided:
44 (a) Adequate fire and smoke alarms;
45 (b) A functional telephone located on the daycare premises during the
46 hours of operation;

4
1 (c) Adequate fire extinguishers;
2 (d) Adequate exits;
3 (e) Firearms or other weapons which are stored on the premises of a day-
4 care facility must be kept in a locked container that is inaccessible to
5 children while daycare attendees are present;
6 (f) Pools, hot tubs, ponds and other bodies of water that are on the day-
7 care facility premises must provide the following safeguards:
8 (i) The area surrounding the body of water must be fenced and
9 locked in a manner that prevents access by children and meets the
10 following requirements:
11 1. The fence must be at least four (4) feet high with no ver-
12 tical opening more than four (4) inches wide, be designed so
13 that a young child cannot climb or squeeze under or through
14 the fence, surround all sides of the pool and have a gate that
15 is self-closing and that has a self-latching mechanism in
16 proper working order out of the reach of young children;
17 2. If the house forms one (1) side of the barrier for the
18 pool, all doors that provide unrestricted access to the pool
19 must have alarms that produce an audible sound when the door
20 is opened;
21 3. Furniture or other large objects must not be left near the
22 fence in a manner that would enable a child to climb on the
23 furniture or other large object and gain access to the pool;
24 and
25 (ii) If the area surrounding a pool, hot tub, pond or other body of
26 water is not fenced and locked, there must be a secured protective
27 covering that will not allow access by a child;
28 (iii) Wading pools must be empty when not in use;
29 (iv) Children must be under direct supervision of at least one (1)
30 adult employee while using a pool, hot tub, pond or other body of
31 water; and
32 (v) A minimum of a four (4) foot high fence must be present that
33 prevents access from the daycare facility premises if the daycare
34 premises are adjacent to a body of water; and
35 (g) The owner or operator of a daycare facility shall ensure that at
36 all times when a child or children are present, at least one (1) adult
37 employee on the premises has current certification in pediatric rescue
38 breathing and first-aid treatment from a certified instructor.
39 (2) No fire standards developed pursuant to this chapter shall be more
40 stringent than the standards contained in the International Fire Code, as
41 adopted by Idaho.
42 (3) At least one (1) adult employee must be present at all times when a
43 child or children are in attendance.
44 (4) (a) The maximum allowable child:staff ratio shall be a maximum of
45 twelve (12) points per staff member using the following point system:
46 (i) Each child in attendance under the age of twenty-four (24)
47 months shall equal two (2) points.
48 (ii) Each child in attendance from twenty-four (24) months to
49 under thirty-six (36) months of age shall equal one and one-half
50 (1 1/2) points.

5
1 (iii) Each child in attendance from thirty-six (36) months to un-
2 der five (5) years of age shall equal one (1) point.
3 (iv) Each child in attendance from five (5) years to under thir-
4 teen (13) years of age shall equal one-half (1/2) point.
5 (b) Each child in attendance shall be counted by the department for pur-
6 poses of calculating maximum allowable points, counting the number of
7 children in attendance and for determining compliance with child:staff
8 ratios.
9 (4) Daycare facilities shall establish and maintain a child-to-staff
10 ratio appropriate to ensure the health, safety, and welfare of all children
11 in attendance. Each facility shall:
12 (a) Develop a documented child-to-staff ratio policy that accounts for
13 the ages and needs of the children under its care;
14 (b) Ensure the established child-to-staff ratio policy is made readily
15 available to parents and guardians through accessible means and upon
16 request; and
17 (c) Remain in compliance with the documented child-to-staff ratio pol-
18 icy.
19 SECTION 7. That Section 39-1111, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
20 amended to read as follows:
21 39-1111. RULES AUTHORIZED. In order to implement the provisions of
22 this chapter, the department, in addition to other duties imposed by law, is
23 hereby authorized and directed through rulemaking to establish procedures
24 necessary to implement the provisions of this chapter including procedure
25 for submission of required certificates as provided in sections 39-1109
26 and 39-1110, Idaho Code, and to conduct the criminal history check provided
27 in section 39-1105, Idaho Code. The rulemaking authority granted in this
28 section shall be limited to the specific standards and procedures required
29 by this chapter. The department shall seek to move all necessary rules into
30 this chapter by July 1, 2026.
31 SECTION 8. That Section 39-1112A, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
32 amended to read as follows:
33 39-1112A. ACCESS TO INFORMATION. The department shall make available
34 to daycare consumers an informational pamphlet, created by the department,
35 information to educate daycare consumers with informational tools useful in
36 identifying quality daycare. The department may deliver pamphlets during
37 direct contact with daycare consumers, or by delivering pamphlets to day-
38 care providers during the licensing or renewal process, during inspections
39 or through other appropriate means. The pamphlet shall include, including:
40 (1) The importance of parents being vigilant for the safety, emotional
41 health and training of their children that cannot be replaced by any other
42 institution or individual;
43 (2) The basic characteristics of a quality daycare;
44 (3) A strong suggestion to parents to inquire about criminal history
45 checks for any provider in a family daycare home;
46 (4) A link to a department approved website that contains more detailed
47 information; and

6
1 (5) A department or other phone number for parents to report unsafe,
2 dangerous or harmful activities within the daycare.
3 SECTION 9. That Section 39-1115, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
4 amended to read as follows:
5 39-1115. MISDEMEANOR. (1) It shall be a misdemeanor to operate a day-
6 care facility within this state without first obtaining a basic daycare li-
7 cense from the department or to operate a daycare facility without posting a
8 basic daycare license in a conspicuous place. A copy of this chapter shall
9 be available on the premises at all times for staff and parents to read on re-
10 quest unless otherwise exempted by this chapter.
11 (2) If a daycare facility is found to be operating without a license,
12 the licensing agency may grant a grace period of no more than sixty (60) days
13 to allow the daycare facility to come into compliance with the provisions of
14 this chapter.
15 (3) It shall be a misdemeanor to operate a family daycare home caring
16 for four (4) or more children without obtaining and passing the criminal his-
17 tory check required in section 39-1105, Idaho Code; provided, that in the
18 event of an initial citation for violation of the provisions of this subsec-
19 tion, if a person makes the applications required within twenty (20) days,
20 the complaint shall be dismissed. Operation of a family daycare home caring
21 for four (4) or more children after failure to pass a required criminal his-
22 tory check shall be a misdemeanor.
23 (4) It is a misdemeanor for any person to provide daycare services
24 if such person has been found guilty in this state's courts, in any other
25 state's courts, or in any federal court, of any offense listed under the pro-
26 visions of section 39-1113, Idaho Code.
27 SECTION 10. That Section 39-1117, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
28 repealed.
29 SECTION 11. That Section 39-1120, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
30 repealed.
31 SECTION 12. The rules contained in IDAPA 16.06.03, Idaho Department of
32 Health and Welfare, relating to Daycare Licensing, Section 011.08., Section
33 100.06., and Section 300.01., shall be null, void, and of no force and effect
34 on and after the effective date of this act.
35 SECTION 13. An emergency existing therefor, which emergency is hereby
36 declared to exist, this act shall be in full force and effect on and after
37 July 1, 2025.

